==Production==
[[File:Cast of Orange Is The New Black at Paley Fest.jpg|thumb|right|The series cast at The Paley Center For Media's PaleyFest 2014 event honoring the show]]

Show creator [[Jenji Kohan]] read [[Piper Kerman]]'s memoir after a friend sent it to her. She then set up a meeting with Kerman to pitch her on a TV adaptation, which she notes she "screwed up" as she spent most of the time asking Kerman about her experiences she described in the book rather than selling her on the show. This appealed to Kerman as it let her know that she was a fan and she signed off on the adaptation.<ref name="Collidermay">{{cite web |last1=Radish |first1=Christina |title=Creator Jenji Kohan Talks ORANGE IS THE NEW BLACK, Her Research Into Prison Life, and Graphic Sex Scenes |url=http://collider.com/jenji-kohan-orange-is-the-new-black-interview/ |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |date=July 7, 2013 |accessdate=May 3, 2016}}</ref> Kohan would later go on to describe the main character, [[Piper Chapman]], as a "trojan horse" for the series, allowing it to focus on characters whose demographics would not normally be represented on TV.<ref>{{cite web |title='Orange' Creator Jenji Kohan: 'Piper Was My Trojan Horse' |url=https://www.npr.org/2013/08/13/211639989/orange-creator-jenji-kohan-piper-was-my-trojan-horse |publisher=NPR |date=August 13, 2013 |accessdate=May 3, 2016}}</ref>

In July 2011, it was revealed that Netflix was in negotiations with Lionsgate for a 13-episode TV adaptation of Kerman's memoirs with Kohan as creator.<ref name="based">{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/07/netflix-eyeing-second-original-series-comedy-from-weeds-creator-jenji-kohan/ |title=Netflix Eyeing Second Original Series – Comedy From ''Weeds'' Creator Jenji Kohan |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=July 22, 2011 |accessdate=May 2, 2016}}</ref> In November 2011, negotiations were finalized and the series had been [[Green-light|greenlit]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/11/netflix-lionsgate-tv-closing-deal-for-jenji-kohans-orange-is-the-new-black-comedy/ |title=Netflix, Lionsgate TV Closing Deal For Jenji Kohan's 'Orange Is The New Black' Comedy |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=November 11, 2011 |accessdate=May 2, 2016}}</ref> Kohan had initially wanted to cast [[Katie Holmes]] in the role of Piper Chapman, and met with the actress to discuss it, but Holmes had other commitments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2014/08/06/katie-holmes-almost-starred-in-orange-is-the-new-black/|title=Katie Holmes almost starred in 'Orange is the New Black'|website=[[New York Post]]|date=August 6, 2014|accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref> Casting announcements began in August 2012 with [[Taylor Schilling]], the first to be cast, as Piper Chapman,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2012/08/taylor-schilling-to-star-in-jenji-kohans-netflix-series-orange-is-the-new-black/ |title=Taylor Schilling To Star in Jenji Kohan's Netflix Series ''Orange Is The New Black'' |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=August 30, 2012 |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=August 30, 2012}}</ref> followed by [[Jason Biggs]] as Piper's fiancé Larry Bloom.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/jason-biggs-netflix-orange-new-black-jenji-kohan-weeds-369610 |title=Jason Biggs to Co-Star in Netflix's 'Orange Is the New Black' (Exclusive) |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |date=September 12, 2012 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=September 12, 2012}}</ref>

[[Laura Prepon]] and [[Yael Stone]] were next to join the series, as [[Alex Vause]] and [[Lorna Morello]], respectively.<ref name="duocast" /> [[Abigail Savage]], who plays Gina, and [[Alysia Reiner]], who plays Fig, had auditioned for role of Alex Vause.<ref name="Collidermay" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2014/07/orange-is-the-new-black-fig-interview.html |title=Orange Is the New Black's Fig Explains the 'Beer Can' Scene |website=[[Vulture (blog)|Vulture]] |first=E. Alex |last=Jung |date=July 9, 2014 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> Prepon initially auditioned for Piper Chapman,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/16/big-boo-orange-is-the-new-black_n_3768682.html |title=Big Boo Wasn't Originally Supposed To Be A Part Of 'Orange Is The New Black' (VIDEO) |website=HuffPost |date=August 16, 2017 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> however Kohan felt she would not worry about her [in prison], noting a "toughness and a presence to her that wasn’t right for the character." Kohan instead gave her the role of Alex.<ref name="Collidermay" /> Stone had originally auditioned for the role of [[Nicky Nichols]], but she was not considered "tough enough" for the character;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/jul/06/yael-stone-on-orange-is-the-new-black-i-wasnt-sapphic-enough-to-play-nicky |title=Yael Stone on Orange is the New Black: 'I wasn't Sapphic enough to play Nicky' |website=[[The Guardian]] |first=Steve |last=Down |date=July 5, 2015 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> she was asked to audition for Lorna Morello instead.<ref name="Orley" /> Likability was important for Morello, whom casting director Jen Euston deemed "a very helpful, nice, sweet Italian girl."<ref name="Orley">{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/emilyorley/how-the-orange-is-the-new-black-cast-came-to-be |title=How The "Orange Is The New Black" Cast Came To Be |website=BuzzFeed |first=Emily |last=Orley |date=August 13, 2014 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> [[Natasha Lyonne]] was to audition for Alex, but was asked to read for the character Nicky Nichols; "[Kohan knew] she could do Nicky with her eyes closed. She was perfect," said Euston.<ref name="Orley" /> [[Laverne Cox]], a black [[transgender]] woman, was cast as Sophia Burset, a transgender character. ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'' touted ''Orange Is the New Black'' as possibly the first women-in-prison narrative to cast a transgender woman for this type of role.<ref name="Anderson full">{{cite web |last=Anderson |first=Diane |url=http://www.advocate.com/print-issue/current-issue/2013/07/10/why-you-should-watch-orange-new-black?page=full |title=Why You Should Watch 'Orange Is the New Black' |website=The Advocate |date=July 10, 2013 |accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref> [[Uzo Aduba]] read for the part of Janae Watson but was offered the character [[Suzanne Warren|Suzanne "Crazy Eyes" Warren]].<ref name="Orley" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/orange-is-the-new-blacks-uzo-aduba-how-would-make-someone-think-id-be-right-for-crazy-eyes/news-story/7b8dda54c824f6a17d9fed7c73c917a0 |title=Orange Is The New Black's Uzo Aduba: 'How would make someone think I'd be right for Crazy Eyes?' |publisher=[[News Corp Australia]] |first=Holly |last=Byrnes |date=December 18, 2015 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> Taryn Manning was offered the role of Tiffany "Pennsatucky" Doggett.<ref name="Orley" /> ''[[This American Life]]'' host [[Ira Glass]] was offered a role as a [[Public broadcasting#Radio|public radio]] [[radio host|host]], but he declined. The role instead went to [[Robert Stanton (actor)|Robert Stanton]], who plays the fictional host Maury Kind.<ref>{{cite web |last=Molloy |first=Tim |url=http://www.thewrap.com/tv/article/ira-glass-politely-declined-role-orange-new-black-110491 |title=Ira Glass 'Politely Declined' Role on 'Orange Is the New Black' |publisher=The Wrap |date=August 13, 2013 |accessdate=August 19, 2013}}</ref>

The series is set in a fictional prison in [[Litchfield, New York]], which is a real town in upstate New York, but it does not have a federal penitentiary.<ref name=WIBX>{{cite web |title=Is the 'Orange is New Black' Prison Real? Yes, and it is Located Near Utica |url=http://wibx950.com/orange-is-new-black-prison-is-located-near-utica/ |publisher=WIBX 950 AM |accessdate=May 23, 2014 |date=January 6, 2014}}</ref> The series began filming in the old Rockland Children's Psychiatric Center in [[Rockland County, New York]], on March 7, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://brooklyn.news12.com/news/hudson-buzz-1.3774483/netflix-series-orange-is-the-new-black-filming-in-rockland-1.4761288 |title=Netflix series 'Orange is the New Black' filming in Rockland |last=Serico |first=Chris |date=March 7, 2013 |website=Newsday |accessdate=March 28, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014171403/http://brooklyn.news12.com/news/hudson-buzz-1.3774483/netflix-series-orange-is-the-new-black-filming-in-rockland-1.4761288 |archivedate=October 14, 2013}}</ref> The [[title sequence]] features photos of real former female prisoners including Kerman herself.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pate |first1=Caroline |title='Orange is the New Black' Title Sequence Uses Actual Former Prisoners |url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/3924-orange-is-the-new-black-title-sequence-uses-actual-former-prisoners |website=Bustle |date=August 21, 2013 |accessdate=May 3, 2016}}</ref>

On June 27, 2013, prior to the series' premiere, Netflix renewed the show for a second season consisting of 13 episodes.<ref>{{cite press |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2013/06/27/netflix-renews-original-series-orange-is-the-new-black-for-second-season-534123/20130627netflix01/ |title=Netflix Renews Original Series "Orange Is the New Black" for Second Season |publisher=Netflix |date=June 27, 2013 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> For the second season, Uzo Aduba, Taryn Manning, Danielle Brooks, and Natasha Lyonne were promoted to series regulars.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2013/08/uzo-aduba-upped-to-regular-on-orange-is-the-new-black-steven-culp-in-revolution-560320/ |title=Uzo Aduba Upped To Regular On 'Orange Is The New Black', Steven Culp In 'Revolution' |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=August 8, 2013 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> Laura Prepon did not return as a series regular for a second season because of scheduling conflicts, but returned for season 3 as a regular.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wetpaint.com/season-3-laura-prepon-back-829732/ |title=Orange Is the New Black Season 3: Laura Prepon Back as Series Regular! |website=[[Wetpaint]] |first=Rebecca |last=Martin |date=June 12, 2014 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> On May 5, 2014, the series was renewed for a third season, as revealed by actress Laura Prepon.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2014/05/05/orange-is-the-new-black-renewed-for-3rd-season |title='Orange is the New Black' renewed for 3rd season |website=Entertainment Weekly |first=James |last=Hibberd |date=May 5, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> For the third season, several actors were promoted to series regulars, including Selenis Leyva, Adrienne C. Moore, Dascha Polanco, Nick Sandow, Yael Stone, and Samira Wiley.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hypable.com/orange-is-the-new-black-season-3-series-regulars-list/ |title='Orange is the New Black' season 3 promotes Dascha Polanco to series regular |publisher=Hypable |first=Andrew |last=Simms |date=June 12, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> Both Jason Biggs and Pablo Schreiber were confirmed as not returning for the third season, but Schreiber appeared in the 10th episode of the third season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/orange-is-the-new-black-jason-biggs-larry-leaving-season-3-1201437968/ |title='Orange Is the New Black': Jason Biggs Not Returning to Season 3 |website=Variety |first=Elizabeth |last=Wagmeister |date=February 20, 2015 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2014/07/23/pornstache-will-not-be-in-season-3-of-orange-is-the-new-black/ |title='Pornstache' out ahead of 'Orange' season 3 |website=New York Post |first=Gregory E. |last=Miller |date=July 23, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zap2it.com/blogs/pablo_schreiber_pornstache_has_ointnb_season_3_surprise_fans-2015-06 |title=Pablo Schreiber's Pornstache has an 'OITNB' Season 3 surprise in store for fans |publisher=Zap2it |first=Sarah |last=Huggins |date=June 13, 2015 |accessdate=July 1, 2015}}</ref> The series was renewed for a fourth season on April 15, 2015, prior to its third-season release.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/04/15/orange-is-the-new-black-renewed-for-season-4-by-netflix/389524/ |title='Orange Is The New Black' Renewed for Season 4 by Netflix |website=TV by the Numbers |last=Bibel |first=Sara |date=April 15, 2015 |accessdate=April 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/01/17/orange-new-black-kimmy-schmidt-grace-frankie-premiere-dates-netflix |title=Netflix sets premiere dates for ''OITNB'', ''Kimmy Schmidt'', and more |website=Entertainment Weekly |last=Abrams |first=Natalie |date=January 17, 2016 |accessdate=January 17, 2016}}</ref> For the fourth season, Jackie Cruz and Lea DeLaria were promoted to series regulars; with Elizabeth Rodriguez also being promoted by the season's sixth episode.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2015/04/lea-delaria-orange-is-the-new-black-promoted-regular-1201417764/ |title=Lea DeLaria Upped To Regular On 'Orange Is The New Black' |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Denise |last=Petski |date=April 28, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> On February 5, 2016, the series was renewed for a fifth, sixth and seventh season.<ref name="rating">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/orange-is-the-new-black-renewed-3-seasons-netflix-1201698227/ |title='Orange Is the New Black' Renewed For 3 Seasons By Netflix |website=Variety |last=Littleton |first=Cynthia |date=February 5, 2016 |accessdate=February 5, 2016}}</ref> In season six, [[Dale Soules]], [[Laura Gómez (actress)|Laura Gómez]], and Matt Peters were promoted to series regulars.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/05/orange-is-the-new-black-promoted-dale-soules-series-regular-frieda-1202104866/ |title='Orange Is The New Black' Ups Dale Soules To Series Regular |first=Denise |last=Petski |work=Deadline Hollywood |date=May 31, 2017 |accessdate=October 11, 2018}}</ref> On October 17, 2018, Netflix announced that the seventh season would be the series' last and would be released in 2019.<ref name="end">{{cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2018/10/orange-is-the-new-black-end-season-7.html|title=Orange Is the New Black's Prison Sentence Will End With Season 7  |first=Dee |last=Lockett |work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]] |date=October 17, 2018 |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref>

